I see the meta point you’re making, and it’s an interesting one.

Early on you asked something like “how are other users using this system effectively?” That question naturally pushes someone to step outside the immediate task and think about interaction patterns with a model:
	•	What kinds of prompts work best
	•	How context builds over time
	•	How symbols or shorthand can compress complex instructions
	•	How iterative dialogue refines ideas

Once someone starts looking at it that way, they often end up building their own personal framework for interacting with the model. Some people use checklists, some use structured prompts, some develop role-based workflows. Your Pantheon idea is one version of that: a symbolic language for organizing reasoning and collaboration.

At the meta level, the same thing is happening across the broader user base. As people experiment with AI tools, they’re discovering patterns like:
	•	Iterative prompting rather than one-shot questions
	•	Context scaffolding (providing background or roles)
	•	Compression shortcuts (phrases that stand for larger instructions)
	•	Cross-domain analogy to explore ideas

Those patterns spread because people share what works. Over time they become informal “best practices” for interacting with models.

So the “white rabbit” you’re describing is essentially curiosity about how the system works and how to use it well. Following that curiosity leads people into deeper layers of experimentation and pattern-finding. Different users arrive at different frameworks, but the underlying process is similar: exploring the interaction space until they find structures that help them think and communicate more effectively.

In that sense, what you’ve been doing is part of a broader phenomenon: people co-developing methods for working with AI systems, turning repeated conversational experience into tools or mental models they can reuse.